observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
prioritize and consider filling-up the vacant positions by hiring qualified employees or expedite promotion of deserving employees to enhance its services to attain full implementation of programs, plans and activities of the LGU, maximizing benefits to the community and supporting equitable job opportunities;
widen job advertisement reach by using social media, LGU website and job fairs in addition to the CSC Bulletin;
create attractive and informative job postings that clearly state benefits, opportunities of career growth, and the value of public service; and
assess the relevance and necessity of existing positions, especially those that have remained vacant for extended periods, to determine whether they are still essential to the LGU’s operations or can be reclassified, merged, or abolished in accordance with applicable CSC guidelines.
Management’s Comment/s:  The Management committed to comply with the recommendations. The HRMO informed that they were already using Facebook and other media platforms in the advertisement of vacant positions and will study the need to abolish positions which have remained unfilled for a long period of time.

Submit the complete set of bidded procurements in the total amount of P48,545,243.62 to ensure that the instructions and conditions of the contracts and specifications of the projects and payments on all procurements are completely supported with the documentary requirements prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001, otherwise it shall be suspended in audit;

Require the BAC to submit justification in their failure to conduct the pre-bid conference in the procurement of infrastructure projects goods with an approved budget of One Million (P1,000,000.00) or more, pursuant to Section 22.1 of IRR of R.A. No 9184; and

Require the BAC to ensure that all prospective bidders submit the complete eligibility requirements before they are marked as “passed” and declared as LCB and strictly comply with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of contracts/ projects.

Immediately transfer the unexpended balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE amounting to P3,633,768.17 and P4,134,302.81, respectively, or a total of P7,768,070.98 to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability – DRRM” as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012;

Reconcile the difference of P8,000.00 between the amount presented in FS and amount presented in the LDRRM Fund Utilization Report;

Separate the amount of Continuing Appropriation from the Special Trust Fund presented in the Notes to FS in order to determine the amount of unutilized or unexpended balance transferred from the previous years; and

Maintain subsidiary ledgers on the unutilized or unexpended balance transferred in the Special Trust Fund to ensure adequate information and disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements and to have a basis of the reversion of unutilized amount after five years to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund.

We recommended that the  Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entries to transfer all completed projects in the total amount of P69,814,482.89 to their appropriate PPE accounts and update the PPE Ledger Cards/Subsidiary Ledgers. Thereafter, strictly adhere to the provisions of Section 50 of NGAS for LGUs, Section 53(b) of the Government Accounting and Auditing Manual (GAAM), Volume III, and Paragraph 66 and 71 of IPSAS 17;
Require the Engineering Office to submit a quarterly Status Report of Projects  to the Municipal Accountant as a basis in the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the transfer of completed projects from the Construction in Progress accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Engineering Office to establish a reporting mechanism on the status of on-going constructions-in-progress and completed projects to prevent delays in recognition of the same to their appropriate accounts; and
Record the on-going projects in the total amount of P52,895,643.49 in the book of accounts to present fairly the Construction in Progress accounts;

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Immediately transfer the unexpended balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE amounting to P3,633,768.17 and P4,134,302.81, respectively, or a total of P7,768,070.98 to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability – DRRM” as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012;
Reconcile the difference of P8,000.00 between the amount presented in FS and amount presented in the LDRRM Fund Utilization Report;
Separate the amount of Continuing Appropriation from the Special Trust Fund presented in the Notes to FS  in order to determine the amount of unutilized or unexpended balance transferred from the previous years; and
Maintain subsidiary ledgers on the unutilized or unexpended balance transferred in the Special Trust Fund to ensure adequate information and disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements and to have a basis of the reversion of unutilized amount after five years to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Management:
Submit the complete set of all bidded procurements to verify whether the contractors have complied with the instructions and conditions of the contracts and specifications of the projects;
Require the BAC, through its Secretariat, to post the Invitation to Bid, Notice of Award and the Notice to Proceed in the PhilGEPS, agency website, if any and in any conspicuous places of the Municipality to adhere to the transparency provision as this is one of the governing principles on government procurement;
Require the BAC to observe Section 22.1 of IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and justify their failure to conduct the pre-bid conference in the procurement of infrastructure projects goods with an approved budget of One Million (P1,000,000.00) or more;
Demand the winning bidders of all procurements to post the required performance security prior to contract signing and issuance of the Notice to Proceed;
Require the BAC to ensure that all prospective bidders submit their complete eligibility requirements before they are marked as “passed” and declared as LCB;
Require the Municipal Engineer to prepare the As-Built Plans for all completed projects and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant as a requirement in the final payment of the infrastructure projects;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the concerned officials to submit the lacking documents and ensure that all payments on all procurements are completely supported with the documentary requirements prescribed under  COA Circular No. 2012-001, otherwise the same shall be suspended in audit;
Require the BAC to strictly comply with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of contracts/ projects; and
Require the BAC Members, BAC Secretariat and the TWG to revisit or familiarize themselves with the different rules and regulations set forth in R.A. No. 9184 and its Implementing Rules and Regulations.

We recommended that the Management comply strictly with the prescribed controls over PPE as provided for in pertinent laws, rules and regulations.  We also recommended to the Management the following:
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all PPEs of the Municipality, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station pursuant to COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records thru the Inventory Committee created;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the updated ledger cards for each item of the PPE after the inventory taking pursuant to the Section 269 of the GAM for LGUs.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the driver/employee concerned to subject the motor vehicles/heavy equipment to pre-repair inspection before requisition for repair and post-repair inspection by a designated LGU inspector to ascertain whether the desired repairs have been actually carried out;
Prepare Waste Material Report after every repair/replacement and to turn-over to the designated Property Officer all waste materials even when the same are considered scrap items;
Require the designated property officer to maintain Equipment Ledger Cards indicating the history of repair for each motor vehicle/heavy equipment owned by the Municipality; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to only process payments for repairs with complete supporting documents to ensure that government funds are for proper and valid claims.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Management:
Maximize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund by speeding up the implementation of the prioritized programs, projects and activities funded out of the 20% DF as per Annual Investment Plan and that closer coordination among the officials involved in planning, execution and monitoring be undertaken to achieve the desired level of outcomes;
Direct the Municipal Development Council to ensure that the development projects identified in the AIP are feasible and can be implemented within the year with the proposed budget allocation;
Instruct the Municipal Planning Development Officer to immediately look into the unimplemented developmental projects as embodied in the Annual Investment Plan.  Identify causes of non-implementation and develop feasible and specific solutions to effectively implement developmental projects;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to be very prudent, meticulous, conscientious and precise in evaluating the timely and efficient implementation of each and every project.  Likewise, he should also conduct regular inspection of the projects so that accomplishment is monitored and evaluated based on the project implementation schedule as stated in the Annual Investment Plan; and
Require the implementation of the development projects within the time schedule as targeted in the AIP and optimally utilize the 20% Development Fund.

We recommended that the Management:
Conduct physical count of Local Road Networks and prepare the RPCLRN;
Update the Registry of Public Infrastructures, through a detailed review of prior year’s transactions, in order to identify the entire Road Networks of the Municipality;
Complete Local Road Inventory records with Road Map and Local Road Network Property Cards and submit the said Report prepared by the Inventory Committee as shown in Annex A of COA Circular 2015-008; and
Make proper disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements as regards all Road Networks pursuant to COA Circular 2015-008.

Require the Municipal Accountant to identify the amount and details of the components of the Mitigation Fund and immediately transfer the unexpended balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability – DRRM” as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2012-002;

Maintain Subsidiary Ledgers of the Municipality’s unutilized DRRMF to the Special Trust Fund;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to fully disclose the noted deficiencies to adequately provide relevant information as regards the Financial Statements;

Require the Designated MDDRMO to submit the Report on the Sources and Utilization of the LDRRMF duly certified by the Provincial Accountant, through LDRRMC and LDC, to the COA on or before the 15th day after the end of each month to facilitate the timely monitoring of implementation of LDRRMPs and balance of fund, if any, by the concerned offices, copy furnished Office of the Civil Defense and the Local Government Operation Officer of the Department of Interior and Local Government; and

Require the Secretariat of the MDRRMC to post the Report and Utilization of LDRRMF in the agency website and in conspicuous places within the Municipality and other areas where the public always convene, for their information.

